│ The bug is caused by an incorrect transformation in the                                 │
│ `separate-const-offset-from-gep` pass, which does not correctly handle `trunc nsw`      │
│ instructions. The pass attempts to distribute a `trunc` through an `add`, transforming  │
│ `trunc(add(X, C))` into `add(trunc(X), C)`. This is invalid when the `trunc` has `nsw`  │
│ or `nuw` flags, as it can change a well-defined operation into one that produces        │
│ poison.                                                                                 │
│                                                                                         │
│ The function responsible for this transformation is `ConstantOffsetExtractor::find`. It │
│ recursively traverses the expression tree to find a constant offset. When it encounters │
│ a `trunc` instruction, it recursively calls `find` on the operand of the `trunc` and    │
│ then applies the truncation to the result. This is where the incorrect distribution     │
│ happens.                                                                                │
│                                                                                         │
│ To fix this, I will modify `ConstantOffsetExtractor::find`. Before recursively          │
│ processing the operand of a `TruncInst`, I will check if the instruction has `nsw` or   │
│ `nuw` flags. If it does, I will not trace into it, effectively stopping the incorrect   │
│ transformation. This ensures that the semantics of `nsw` and `nuw` are respected.       │
│                                                                                         │
