│ The bug is that `separate-const-offset-from-gep` incorrectly transforms `trunc nsw (add │
│ i128 %i, 1)` into `add (trunc nsw i128 %i), 1`. This is wrong because `trunc nsw` does  │
│ not distribute over `add`.                                                              │
│                                                                                         │
│ The transformation is performed in `ConstantOffsetExtractor::find`. When it sees a      │
│ `trunc`, it recursively calls `find` on the operand. If the operand is an `add`, `find` │
│ will trace into it via `findInEitherOperand`, effectively distributing the `trunc`.     │
│                                                                                         │
│ To fix this, I will modify `find` to prevent it from tracing into an `add` if it's      │
│ under a `trunc` with `nsw` or `nuw`.                                                    │
│                                                                                         │
│ I will modify the `TruncInst` case in `ConstantOffsetExtractor::find`.                  │
